The article discusses the U.S. financial reform and the agenda of the G-20 leaders. It highlights the key provisions of the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, which puts the U.S. at the forefront of global financial reform. The article emphasizes the goal of ending the concept of "too big to fail" and ensuring that taxpayers do not bear the cost of resolution for failing financial firms. It also mentions the implementation of stronger capital requirements, transparency in derivatives markets, and closing loopholes in the regulation of major financial firms. Additionally, the article discusses the registration and disclosure requirements for hedge funds, constraints on the size and risks of the largest firms, reforms in pay practices, separation of banking and speculative trading, and the establishment of a Consumer Financial Protection Bureau. The article concludes by noting that the financial reforms aim to support long-term job growth and prevent future crises.